# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral Instruct v0.3 (e.g. `mistralai/Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407`) uses a
distinct Jinja template that:
- Wraps every user turn with `[INST]…[/INST]`  
- Prepends any system message to the **first** user turn (inline, separated by
  `\n\n`)
- Appends `</s>` after every assistant turn
- Announces tools with `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS][…][/AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` (not the
  `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` used by Ministral / v7)
- Emits tool calls as `[TOOL_CALLS][{"name":…,"arguments":…,"id":…}]</s>`
- Returns tool results with `[TOOL_RESULTS]…[/TOOL_RESULTS]`

The existing `common_chat_try_specialized_template` in `common/chat.cpp` handles
Ministral 3 by detecting `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` + `[TOOL_CALLS]` + `[ARGS]`.  The
Mistral Instruct v0.3 format has none of those (`[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, `[ARGS]`) and
currently falls through to the differential autoparser.  A dedicated handler
gives explicit, predictable parsing and matches the pattern of the other seven
specialised handlers already in the file.

**Constraint:** Only new code may be added.  Existing handler functions and the
header file (`common/chat.h`) must not be changed.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | Only file to be edited — new handler function + new detection clause |
| `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja` | Reference template that defines the exact token markers |
| `common/chat-peg-parser.h` | `common_chat_peg_builder` API, including `standard_json_tools()` |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | Legacy detection (read-only; confirms `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` ↔ v3) |

---

## Implementation Steps

### Step 1 — New handler function

Insert `common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3` in `common/chat.cpp`
**after** the closing `}` of `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` (≈ line 1517)
and **before** `namespace workaround {` (≈ line 1519).

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {

    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;
    data.preserved_tokens  = { "[TOOL_CALLS]" };

    auto has_tools       = inputs.tools.is_array() && !inputs.tools.empty();
    auto include_grammar = has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        // generation_prompt prefix; "[TOOL_CALLS]" is the lookahead delimiter
        auto generation_prompt = p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt, "[TOOL_CALLS]");

        if (!has_tools || inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE) {
            include_grammar = false;
            return generation_prompt + p.content(p.rest());
        }

        // Mistral v3 tool call format:
        //   [TOOL_CALLS][{"name":"…","arguments":{…},"id":"…"}, …]
        // standard_json_tools handles the array-wrapped JSON list.
        auto tools_parser = p.standard_json_tools(
            "[TOOL_CALLS]",          // section_start (literal prefix)
            "",                      // section_end   (EOS token follows)
            inputs.tools,
            inputs.parallel_tool_calls,
            inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_REQUIRED,
            "name",                  // name_key
            "arguments",             // args_key
            /* array_wrapped    = */ true,
            /* function_is_key  = */ false,
            "id",                    // call_id_key  (9-char alphanumeric)
            "",                      // gen_call_id_key (none)
            { "name", "arguments", "id" }  // parameters_order (matches template)
        );

        return generation_prompt + p.content(p.until("[TOOL_CALLS]")) + tools_parser;
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    if (include_grammar) {
        data.grammar_lazy = has_tools && inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_AUTO;

        data.grammar = build_grammar([&](const common_grammar_builder & builder) {
            foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
                const auto & function = tool.at("function");
                auto         schema   = function.at("parameters");
                builder.resolve_refs(schema);
            });
            parser.build_grammar(builder, data.grammar_lazy);
        });

        data.grammar_triggers = {
            { COMMON_GRAMMAR_TRIGGER_TYPE_WORD, "[TOOL_CALLS]" }
        };
    }

    return data;
}
```

### Step 2 — Register in auto-detection

Inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template` (≈ lines 1634–1691), add a new
`if` block **after** the GigaChatV3 detection (≈ line 1688) and **before**
`return std::nullopt;` (≈ line 1690):

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 (e.g. Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407)
    // Signature: [INST]/[/INST] user turns + [AVAILABLE_TOOLS] for tool
    // descriptions.  Distinguished from Ministral 3 / v7 by the *absence* of
    // [SYSTEM_PROMPT] (which those formats require).
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v0.3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Why these three conditions are safe:**
- `[INST]` + `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` together uniquely identify the v3 family.
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent rules out Ministral 3 (already handled above) and v7.
- Plain v1 templates don't contain `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]`, so they fall through to
  the autoparser as before.
- None of the other seven existing detection branches match on `[INST]` or
  `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]`, so there is no ordering conflict.

---

## Reused Utilities

| Utility | Location | Used for |
|---------|----------|---------|
| `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl` | `common/chat.cpp` ~line 820 | render prompt from Jinja template |
| `build_chat_peg_parser` | `common/chat.cpp` | construct the PEG parser object |
| `common_chat_peg_builder::prefix` | `common/chat-peg-parser.h` | consume generation-prompt prefix |
| `common_chat_peg_builder::standard_json_tools` | `common/chat-peg-parser.h` | parse JSON-array tool call block |
| `common_chat_peg_builder::content` / `until` / `rest` | `common/chat-peg-parser.h` | parse content region |
| `build_grammar` / `foreach_function` | `common/chat.cpp` | constrained JSON grammar |
| `COMMON_GRAMMAR_TRIGGER_TYPE_WORD` | `common/chat.h` | grammar trigger on `[TOOL_CALLS]` |

---

## Verification

1. **Build**: `cmake --build build -j$(nproc) --target test-chat-template` and
   `cmake --build build -j$(nproc) --target test-chat-auto-parser` — both must
   compile and pass with no regressions.

2. **Manual template smoke-test** (content-only):
   ```
   ./build/bin/llama-cli --hf-repo mistralai/Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407 \
     --jinja --chat-template "$(cat models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja)" \
     -p "Hello"
   ```
   Confirm the log line `Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v0.3` appears.

3. **Tool-call path**: supply `--tools` and verify:
   - grammar triggers on `[TOOL_CALLS]`
   - tool name/arguments are correctly extracted from the `[TOOL_CALLS][…]` array
   - `"id"` field (9-char) is parsed without error

4. **Non-regression**: run the existing tests with templates that contain
   `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (Ministral 3) and confirm they still route to their own
   handler (`common_chat_params_init_ministral_3`), not the new one.

